title: Thickened Case for Slim Wallet V2.0 (Updated with better lever design)

description.text:
-----UPDATE - Mar.21.17-----

Added a screw pin/cap, this has less play in the hole, I'd recommend printing these at a 0.14mm layer height or lower to ensure nice threads. Also, I added another lock, similar to the original but I filleted the edges, this should allow you to put it in with some pressure from a screwdriver - this way your cards are nice and secure.

---------UPDATE - Feb.16.17-------------

The lock was a bit of a pain to get in with the new wall thickness, it is now redesigned to allow it to be slid into the upper notch orthogonal to its resting position, once it is sitting sideways in the channel rotate it downward by 90 degrees to lock it in.

Note that this means there is less surface area locking down the cards, so it isn't as firm of a lock compared to the old one, it still holds the cards in just fine (it passed the hold it upside down and shake the hell out of it test).

I have also sliced in a component from another design (the Cardinal Wallet by virustwin) for a more robust money clip, the layers are orthogonal to the load on the clip so it is quite strong.

--------UPDATE - Feb.4.17.-----------------

I did not take into account that the original lever required the case to be bent for it to fit, so the lever was very very difficult to insert with my original revision.

I also think I made it bit too thick, so I have reduced the thickness slightly, and re-designed the lever; the lever now freely slides into its place with a pin/cap that slides through the case/lever to secure it.

This new mechanism seems to work well, the pin and cap should snap together snugly, but feel free to apply a dab of glue if you wish.

-------Original Post---------

I loved the original design and idea, but I wanted this model to be a bit thicker as it felt quite brittle. I also had no need for the money clip; moreover, I noted that some comments on the original design also desired a thicker casing.

I sliced and diced the original casing up, removed the money clip, thickened the front and back and also shaved off the "Pentland Designs" embossing along the edge (I hope that is okay, I didn't want to modify something and still represent the brand).

Enjoy!

description.text: Fan duct for the Anet A8 and similar models. Three versions supplied - one with a shallow connection to the blower, one with a deeper blower connection and one with a deeper blower connection and a slightly longer nozzle to be slightly closer to the hot end. Some dimensions from this model originate from Original fan duct for Anet A8/Hesine/M505++ by mseljestokken - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1438439

Notes:

2 outer layers, supports only from base plate. Model should be laid on one of the two flat sides to print.

The basic dimensions for the connection with the blower and the relative position of the outlet were derived from the linked maker's item. The model was built from a poly cube extruded multiple times and tweaked to form the profile I was looking for. I bevelled the edges of the end closest to the bed to give more clearance from the build plate without changing the direction of airflow. The three versions provided in the download are as follows:

  • Shallow connection to blower - still a snug fit and slightly lighter on filament use.
  • Deeper connection to blower - same dimensions other than this change
  • Slightly longer nozzle end - to bring airflow slightly closer to the part if required.

The mesh itself is fairly light so the three versions still don't leave you with a large file.

All versions have been printed by me once to test whether they made a snug fit. I have printed with the first version attached and as the others have the same clearance from the build plate this should mean that they will all work well.

Summer of 2016 I took a road trip to attend a week long University course. Not entirely prepared when i left, i knew that these screw mounts would come in handy for recording my vlog.
I didn't bring along a tripod or selfie stick but when the first situation came up that required a stable surface to place the Session on, I was able to throw together a stabilizer/selfie stick using a 16" 2x4 cutoff.
It was amusing to me to think what might be going through the minds of bystanders when they saw me talking to a piece of wood.
This piece of lumber went everywhere with me during that week, including into the ocean, in and on a couple of rivers, through the bush...
The lumber aside, I was able to rig up a glove in about 10 minutes using this mount, some rebar tie-down, and some gorilla tape so I could get some sweet footage of me zip-lining for the first time. The glove has since been upgraded to replace the tie-down with rivets, but its definitely staying in my kit.

I suggest printing a few of these. They are very handy to have in your kit...but don't forget to add a few deck screws and a driver. ALSO, print the magnetic mount i made available...add that to the kit too. you can never have enough options. HAVE FUN!

If you're downloading this, please consider tipping a couple bucks so i can afford the time to design more things for you.
If you want this printed and shipped to you, visit my hub: https://goo.gl/ERj059 you can get better pricing on quantities...i might just throw in some gummy bears with your order.

description.text:
WARNING! this is a very complicated print, it requires sanding and cutting and gluing when mounting (how much obviously depends on the quality of your printer). Be prepared to do a couple of tries with different settings and put some work to the printed parts before you get it working.

This is an experiment to see if it is possible to print a working connector using 2.54mm pitch pin-header 2x2 female and male. I've been using pin headers in a lot of experiments so I figures it would be fun to make them look a bit nicer. I will use this connector for a project where an Arduino controls temperature, ventilation and light in my 3D printer cabinet.

I've printed most tests using 0.05mm layer height and the threads work very well, at first they usually snag a bit so you have to work it back and forth gently until they run smooth. I tried several different methods for locking, like flexing pieces on the side that you push in order to release, but the material wasn't up for the job and I wanted the project to be fully 3D-printed except only the pin headers, so I changed to a locking ring system where the locker ring is turned to lock the connector in place. It's not a super-strong lock as it's only a very tiny bulge on the locker ring that actually locks the connector, but it will prevent it from falling out too easily. I will probably release a couple of iterations to this one whenever I have a need for a new version.

The design was inspired by Lemo and made using Fusion 360.

Cheers and happy printing! :)

Works very well with Prusa PLA. Haven't tested with other materials, please report in the comments if you try with other materials, would be nice to see the result!

What do do when you've printed the parts

The print layers leave tiny threads on the surface and if the connector is printed with rough surfaces those threads can make the connector snag extremely hard, so hard in fact that I had trouble getting it out at all at first. So make sure you try to push it in gently and sand the pieces until the male and female fits together nice and smooth. The pins will add extra friction later so don't be worried that the fit is too floppy, it's much worse if you can't get the connector out.

Important tip!

When assembling the male connector, you obviously first put the cable through the male outer shell, the clamp, the locker ring and the male housing, and solder the 2x2 pin header. Than when you have pushed the pin header into the male insert, it's very important that you get the male insert in the right orientation when you push it into the male housing. The easiest way to do this is to use the female housing by sliding in the pins into the female connector and than using that to push the insert into the male housing and you'll automatically get it in in at the right angle and distance. The fit needs to be really snug, you can use glue to keep the insert in place.

comments.text: Hi, they are tricky for sure. I printed a number of sets before I nailed the settings for mine, but they are dependent on both material used, printer used and the calibration. But even the ones that ended up working were very hard to assemble at first. What I do is turn them back and forth many times, pressing a little bit further every time. In that way, you smooth out the threads. If that doesn't work, try scale up the outer part slightly. Also the fit between the male and female housings are tight and with the layer texture they can snag very hard so you might need to sand away the layers, or use any other smoothing technique.

title: XYZ Da Vinci 1.0A Part Cooling Duct

description.text:
This part cooling duct snakes its way underneath the carriage between the timing belts of the x-axis to the extrusion head. It has been designed to force two streams of air at the tip of the extrusion head. I've tried to get those streams of air perpendicular to one another.
The duct is designed to have a piece of tubing inserted into one side, which can exit the printer through the opening roof panel. That tube can then be connected to whatever means of pressurising air you have. I have found an aquarium air pump works well as it is designed to be relatively quiet, run continuously, and be adjustable. This external pump configuration has the benefit of keeping the weight of the carriage down.

The photos show the difference that having this part cooling system makes. Those prints differ ONLY by the application of the part cooling system.

Ideally one would modify the Repeiter firmware so that the control line going to the extruder fan can be used instead to control the air pump connected to this duct. The existing extruder fan should be fine with with a fixed speed output.

I would love to hear from anyone who gives this part a try, whether positive or negative comments.

title: Blower Fan Active Cooling for Replicator 1 / Flashforge / CTC

description.text:
Active cooling is an absolute necessity for printing with PLA. It just doesn't cool fast enough to get good results otherwise. Axial fans do not provide the CFM and pressure to adequately do this job, in my humble, non-fluid-fluent opinion. Hell, I don't even know what laminar vs turbulent flow is. But a blower fan will provide more of what you want for this application than an 'axial' fan. Sometimes it seems too much, but my PLA parts have fine sharp edges so I thought I'd share what I've been sitting on for 2 years now.

Warning: The fit and finish is not perfect. I pride myself on releasing quality parts that actually print and work as intended, but this can be of use to many and I have sat on it for at least 2 years with minimal updates. Just print it as it seems, you might need to file to fit. Try to file the easily replaceable mount that screws into the fans, not the duct itself.

FET install is easy, but I hear newer printers come with this FET already. If you come across a tutorial and want me to edit this to put it here for reference, feel free to post. Since this is merely a blower fan version of the files it is remixed from, please see them for a proper reference text.

The non 'not4printing' version contains tiny supports that will support the directional fins I added to point the airflow down at the part, and not just cooling the nozzle without requiring printing 'with supports'. Print the 'Coolduct2.1.stl' without supports. I used 30% infill, 2 shells, .1 mm layer height. Break off the support structure. YMMV.

Inevitably, the blower fan has so much CFM that my nozzle and power supply can only maintain ~224 C equilibrium but this is ok, my prints are dank AF and y'all should be jelly. /s

Again, I apologize for releasing such shoddy works, I hope to clean it up later, but I'm sure it'll still be useful and I think this is what I would print today, if I were in the market for a free active cooling solution on Thingiverse.

Oh and if you mount a door/enclosure on your printer, it may not work when the printer reaches its maximum range of travel to the front. Still haven't gotten around to that one though so not a problem for me. Have fun ;)

description.text:
This is a simple brine shrimp hatchery base for culturing brine shrimp for fish breeders.
Print it out and screw on a plastic 2 liter bottle with it's base cut off (see photo at left). 
Once printed, I suggest brushing the inside with acetone to make it water tight. Optionally, add a rubber o-ring at the bottom of the threads to help seal it even more. Attach the airline from your air pump to the nipple protruding vertically from the hatchery base.
Make sure to use an airline check valve in case of a power outage as one does not want the water in this hatchery to back flow into the air pump.

Requires "2LscrewPositive.11.stl" from "2 Liter bottle threads" found at: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:10489 Place this file in the same directory as the scad file from this thing if you wish to modify it. I'd recommend printing this at a high percent infill and with 2 shells in order to waterproof it further. Coating the inside with acetone or an ABS/acetone mix helps too. The o-ring that I ended up using was a simple red-brown o-ring used for sealing the connections for garden hoses. I bought a 10-pack for $1.37 at my local hardware store. For information on how to culture brine shrimp, please see the following articles:

  • The Breeder's Net: Artemia Nauplii As A Food Source
    By Frank Marini, Ph.D.
    http://www.advancedaquarist.com/2002/12/breeder

  • Breeder's Net : Amazing Artemia!
    By Suzy Applegarth
    http://www.advancedaquarist.com/2008/3/breeder
    • If you are interested in breeding marine fish, I highly suggest checking out the Marine Breeding Initiative at http://mbisite.org/ Enjoy!

The purpose of this model was to develop a method for students to quickly make coins and medallions for a mystery artifact history project. https://designmaketeach.com/2017/01/11/mystery-artifact-lesson/ Student have struggled to make convincing replica coin/medallion designs in Tinkercad. I found a bust of Frederick Douglass http://www.123dapp.com/123C-3D-Model/Historical-Bust--Frederick-Douglass/751586 and then imported it into Meshmixer. I plane cut away the base and then plane cut the model in half. I transformed the model in one axis and flatten the model. I exported the model as an STL then imported it into Tinkercad. title: O Scale Modular Tunnel Portal for Lionel or MTH Trains
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a tunnel portal for O Scale Model trains like Lionel or MTH. The exterior dimensions are based off the MTH single and double track tunnel portals. The internal dimensions have been expanded to give more room for trains when the portals are installed near curves.

This is a modular design that can be printed on smaller 3d printers like the Davinci Mini. The internal dimensions of the portals when assembled are:

217mm double track width ~8.5 inches
127mm single track width ~5 inches
146mm height ~5.75 inches

You can print the base pieces and rear connectors without supports. Both upper sections and the keystone need to be printed with supports. I used a .2 resolution with a 15% infill on my Davinci Mini and it turned out really good and took about 20 hours to print.

After printing I assembled the parts with gorilla glue. The connectors snap in enough to hold it well but you will want to glue it. The keystone must be glued in place.

I've updated the keystone_blank.stl file and removed the personalized one. I also made the keystone recessed instead of sticking out. I think it looks better that way.

I don't have a heated bed and have had some pull up on the tops of the top_right and top_left files. Rafts are optional on those if the pull up is too much for you. I can live with it.

Update 3-16-2017:
I've added an alternate top for a double portal that incorporates the expander into the top left and top right parts. This allows you to create a double track portal without any seams visible when using the keystone. I have made these solid. After printing several of these I've found I get less warping if I have it sold and do a honeycomb infill at 10%. Because it was forcing supports in those locations I'm actually using nearly the same amount of filament when printed at .2 resolution and 10% infill. The new files are:

top_left_double_solid.stl
top_right_double_solid.stl

After printing 2 of the singles and one of the doubles I recommend printing the connectors and two bottom pieces at .2 resolution with a 10 infill no supports. The Top portions need a .2 resolution with a 10 infill with supports due to the curve and cavities. For the keystone, once you add text, I recommend a .1 resolution with a 10 infill with supports. It's taking me about 24 hours to print a whole portal.

An automatic DSLR rig for capturing 2D/3D panorama and 360 photosphere (rotates around no-parallax point). It is also designed for capturing dense outward lightfield on a sphere of radius around 20cm (no-parallax point on a sphere) -- to hopefully create stereoscopic full-parallax rendering for VR.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=48YIlS8Qiso

2D Stitched Photoshere: https://goo.gl/photos/Rne65gYcaWQnx26o7
3D Anaglyph Photosphere : https://goo.gl/photos/1s5AUaHT2Pbz3pza7
3D Parallax Photosphere: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1oWBsR8zTP0
3D Stereoscopic Photosphere for VR (Google cardboard camera format): https://goo.gl/photos/61VhSRtq2Ka4yDVn7 (Download and put it in DCIM/CardboardCamera of an Android phone)

The design is inspired by Phil Warner's panobot (https://www.flickr.com/photos/philwarner/sets/72157603776902016/). I tried to make it as compact as possible with one battery source. It has a screen showing menu and options for configuring shots (HDR, rows, cols, angles, etc). The firmware can be updated over Wifi.

It uses:

  1. Two servos from servocity.com (https://www.servocity.com/cm-d645mw-180-servo-gearbox, https://www.servocity.com/sg-d645mw-cm-400-servo-gearbox)
  2. Wemos D1 for controller (https://www.wemos.cc/product/d1-mini.html
  3. OLED Shield (https://www.wemos.cc/product/oled-shield.html)
  4. Joystick (http://www.ebay.com/itm/201433557483)
  5. 18650 batteries (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00IZT269G)
  6. Battery clips (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00LPOTCAY)
  7. 2.5mm jack (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01GBN1WPQ)
  8. UBEC (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0177Y2PZY)
  9. Tripod screw (http://www.ebay.com/itm/262329788916)
  10. Optocouplers for camera shutter (http://www.ebay.com/itm/262136737476)
  11. Analog Multiplexer 4051 (http://www.ebay.com/itm/231558118246)
  12. 220 Ohms Resistor

This rig is made specifically to rotate around the no-parallax point of Nikon D7200. The original fusion 360 is attached for modification and educational purposes.

The schematic and board designs (Eagle) are also provided.

remixed_from.title: Wanhao i3 v2.1 stock 40mm fan rear mounted duct

description.text:
This is a helix fan duct for a 40mm fan with a blower, designed to redirect, shape and straighten fan's flow with maximum efficiency.

It is designed to be attached to Wanhao i3 v2.1 printing head with 2x 20mm M4 screws with conical cross heads, while the assembly itself is held together with stock M3 screws.
All threads in the holes print well enough with 0.2mm layer and match stock M3 screws.
The bottom most surface of this duct is designed to be at least 2mm from the print bed at minimum Z position.
I also designed appropriate supports, included in the model.

This is an evolution of my previous design with an addition of helix duct inspired by DaveGun's Vortex Fan Shroud. Like my previous design this one is a product of several CFD simulations.

The assembly consists of 3 parts:

  • helix duct with a 40x15mm rectangular exit
  • positioning frame
  • blower duct

I designed it this way to make it possible to switch blowers without having to print the whole thing and also to make it possible to use this efficient helix duct on any printer or in any other application that requires air flow.

I've also included models of 2mm thick dampening inserts to be made from flexible material to reduce noise and vibrations from the fan.

Compared with my previous design this assembly provides even more flow (up to 4.3 CFM which is quite close to theoretical maximum of ~5.5CFM for a 40mm fan) and has much less adverse effect on the nozzle temperature level. It is designed to provide cooling for 2 zones - main flow goes around the nozzle and a limited amount goes directly beneath the nozzle through a separate channel, this allows to maintain high flow rate in general and provide cooling of just extruded material without causing too much temperature drop of the nozzle. I've also included blower version without a small channel to further limit nozzle temperature drop in case you don't need to print any severe overhangs or small parts. 4x 1,5mm holes provide cooling flow to prolong blower life under high temperatures (I printed it from PLA and used it to print at nozzle temperatures as high as 245-250C and it survived the print without noticeable damage).

title: Dried PVAc Bed V2 for PLA Printing
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a print bed suitable for PLA printing.
By using waterproof sandpaper, the double-sided tape is less affected by filament heat than the previous version.

Remixed From

  • Stops warping of ABS & Nylon prints, Enjoy it! by Chris918,
  • printing ABS on Jeans textil BED (Without A Heated Bed) by Medelis
  • Da Vinci Cura Settings - repetier 0.92 by tecan

Requirements

  • High adhesive strength double-sided tape
  • Waterproof sandpaper (around 400 grit)
  • PVAc glue
  • Ruler or palette knife
    Used to spread and flatten PVAc glue.

Steps

  1. Put double-sided tape on glass/acrylic plate
  2. Peel off peeling layer from double-sided tape
  3. Put waterproof sandpaper on double-sided tape
  4. Paint PVAc glue on waterproof sandpaper
  5. Spread PVAc glue and make it flat
  6. Wait for PVAc glue to dry

PLA Printing

  • Distance between print bed and nozzle
    Since PLA sticks easily to PVAc bed, if print bed and nozzle are too close, filaments become perfectly sticked with print bed and will not peel off.
    The distance between the print bed and the nozzle needs to be separated to some extent.

ABS Printing

  • Size of printable 3D model
    I think that a small 3D model is suitable for printing.
    Large 3D models can cause printing to fail.

  • Distance between print bed and nozzle
    When printing with ABS, it is difficult to stick the first layer of raft to the print bed compared with PLA, so it is necessary to set the distance of the nozzle from the print bed to an appropriate value.

  • Heated bed
    When using a heated bed, set it to a temperature lower than the heatproof temperature of double-sided tape.
    However, in this version, it is better to set the temperature of the heated bed to a lower temperature because PVAc layer may be peeled off from waterproof sandpaper.

Slicer Settings

Using a thick double-sided tape will make the print bed thicker as well.
For 3D printers without auto leveling function, it is necessary to physically adjust the height of the print bed, but it takes time.
Adjusting the distance of the nozzle from the print bed on the slicer side saves time.

Slic3r Settings

  • Nozzle distance from the print bed
    Using Slic3r, you can adjust the nozzle distance from the print bed.
    The relevant setting items are shown below.
    • Printer Settings -> General -> Size and coordinates -> Z offset

MatterSlice Settings

  • Nozzle distance from the print bed
    Using MatterSlice, the standard slicer of MatterControl, you can adjust the nozzle distance from the print bed.
    The relevant setting items are shown below.

    • SETTINGS -> Printer -> Print Area -> Z offset
  • Continuous printing from skirt to raft
    MatterSlice can print continuously from the skirt to the raft and you can print the raft first layer perfectly.
    Also, since MatterSlice prints the outer frame on the first layer of raft, it is less likely to fail.
    The relevant setting items are shown below.
    • SETTINGS -> General -> Raft / Priming -> Priming -> Loops

Notes

  • About drying
    It takes about 1 to 2 days for the PVAc glue to dry out by natural drying.
    If you dry with a fan, it dries quickly, but it may cause dust to adhere.
    When drying with a heated bed, set it to a temperature lower than the heatproof temperature of double-sided tape.
  • Necessity of raft
    Surface of the dried PVAc layer is uneven, it is necessary to print with the raft.
  • How to deal with when PVAc layer peeled off
    When peeling off between the waterproof sandpaper and PVAc layer, cut off the peeled PVAc layer and apply new PVAc glue and dry it.
